This paper deals with network performance metrics and protocols for online video gaming, which are typically studied in the computer networks (cs.NI) and game theory (cs.GT) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of network coding (cs.IT) to improve latency in gaming protocols, and presents an analysis of the performance gains achieved. Additionally, the paper touches upon the use of mixed communication protocols with broadcast and unicast flows, which falls under the scope of social and information networks (cs.SI) and multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories.
